Health Module

Observability boundary for service liveness and ledger integrity.

This module does not “prove the system works.”

It proves the system is alive — and whether its constitutional core (the ledger) is trustworthy.

Health endpoints are not features.

They are survival primitives.

Core Principle

Health checks must never crash.
Observability must degrade deterministically.
Internal state must never leak.

If your health endpoint throws, your monitoring lies.

Responsibilities

This module owns:

Base service liveness endpoint

Ledger integrity endpoint

Graceful degradation under internal failure

Controlled status code mapping

Stack-trace suppression

It does not:

Expose internal diagnostics

Validate business invariants

Replace structured monitoring

Reveal sensitive infrastructure details

Service Health Endpoint

GET /health

Returns:

status string

runtime mode

process uptime

timestamp

This is a liveness check.

It answers:

“Is the process running?”

It does not answer:

“Is the system correct?”

Ledger Health Endpoint

GET /health/ledger

Delegates to:

ledgerService.getStatus()

Maps result:

ok → HTTP 200

not ok → HTTP 503

If unexpected failure occurs:

Returns:

status: "CORRUPTED"

ok: false

safe error message

timestamp

Never leaks stack traces.

Never propagates raw errors.

Health endpoints are attack surfaces.

They must be intentionally boring.

Why Ledger Health Is Isolated

Ledger is constitutional infrastructure.

If the ledger is corrupted:

Lifecycle replay fails

Financial causality fails

Governance integrity fails

Separating ledger health prevents:

Masking systemic corruption

Misclassifying service as healthy

Cascading monitoring confusion

Service may be alive.
Ledger may not be trustworthy.

Those are different states.

Status Code Semantics

200 → healthy
503 → degraded or corrupted

503 is intentional.

It signals readiness failure without implying application crash.

Monitoring systems rely on status codes, not narrative JSON.

Invariants

Health endpoints must never throw.

Health endpoints must never leak stack traces.

Ledger health must be isolated from base liveness.

Health endpoints must remain side-effect free.

No database mutation.

No ledger mutation.

No decision mutation.

Break these and observability becomes unreliable.

Graceful Degradation Strategy

Worst-case scenario:

Ledger service throws

Database connection fails

Internal error occurs

Response must still return:

Structured JSON

503 status

Timestamp

Health checks are first responders.

They must not panic.

Deployment Guidance

Mount once in app.ts:

app.use("/api", healthRoutes);

Remove inline handlers.

Avoid duplicate /health endpoints.

Observability must be centralized.

Scalability Considerations

Future expansion may include:

Database connectivity check

Redis availability

Queue health

External provider reachability

Additive only.

Do not pollute base liveness route.

Consider adding:

/health/readiness

/health/dependencies

/health/version

But keep /health minimal.

Failure Modes Considered

Ledger service timeout
→ 503 with safe payload

Unexpected exception
→ 503 with deterministic response

Partial infrastructure outage
→ Service health remains 200, ledger 503

Monitoring misinterpretation
→ Clear HTTP mapping prevents ambiguity

Observability Philosophy

Liveness answers:

“Is the process alive?”

Readiness answers:

“Is the system ready?”

Integrity answers:

“Is the constitutional core trustworthy?”

This module currently covers liveness and ledger integrity.

Do not conflate them.

Security Considerations

Health endpoints:

Should not expose environment variables

Should not reveal database URLs

Should not reveal stack traces

Should not reveal internal IDs

Should not reveal ledger hashes

Health endpoints are public by default in many infrastructures.

Assume they are externally reachable.

Mental Model

If your system is a constitutional state:

The ledger is its constitution.
The health module is its pulse monitor.

The pulse monitor must:

Stay calm

Report honestly

Never panic

Never gossip

When something fails, it should say:

“I am degraded.”
